## Preprocessing:
The raw dataset required several preprocessing steps before it could be used for modeling. First, we cleaned and standardized the data by converting column names to a consistent format and converting inspection dates to datetime format. Rows missing essential inspection information such as inspection dates or scores were removed.
Because the dataset is structured with one row per violation, we aggregated violations so that each row represents a single restaurant inspection. During this step we created new features including counts of violations by category, the number of critical vs. non-critical violations, and the ratio of critical violations.
We also created temporal features such as the number of prior inspections, historical average scores, and score changes between inspections. These features allow the model to capture patterns in a restaurant’s compliance history while avoiding data leakage by only using information from previous inspections.
Missing values produced by historical calculations were filled with zero when appropriate so that all observations could be used for modeling.

## Modeling:
For our modeling section, in order for us to establish a baseline, we decided to train multiple classification models to predict whether a restaurant would receive a poor inspection outcome (such as a B or C). Some of our models include Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoost, which provide a mix of interpretability and predictive power.
In terms of our dataset, it was split into training and testing sets to evaluate model performance. Some of the focuses we had included precision, recall, and F1-score, since correctly identifying high-risk restaurants is more important than overall accuracy. We have seen that based on the historical inspection behaviors, it becomes a strong predictor for future outcomes.

## Problems & Challenges:
There were a couple of challenges that we have dealt with, while working with the NYC inspection dataset. Some of the challenges include structure of the dataset itself, class imbalance, and ethical considerations. For the case of the structure of the dataset,  each violation is recorded as a separate row, a single inspection can appear multiple times in the data. So, we had to restructure the dataset into an inspection-level format before any meaningful modeling could occur. For the case of class imbalance, the majority of restaurants receive an A grade, while B and C grades occur far less frequently. Of course, such imbalance can cause model bias in terms of predicting the majority class. So, we decided to experiment with techniques such as class weighting/resampling. For ethical considerations, this was a concern that was raised in the feedback the professor has provided. Including geographic or socioeconomic features may unintentionally concentrate inspections in poorer neighborhoods, potentially creating a self-reinforcing cycle of increased surveillance. In order to combat this challenge, we  plan to analyze whether geographic features introduce bias and explore ways to balance predictive accuracy with fairness.

